the Black Sea: The Landscapes and Regionality of Hellenistic Cyprus -- tHinterland as a Macroeconomic Factor in the Milesian Colonisation of the Northern Black Sea Area (the Case of the Twin Cities of Borysthenes–Olbia) -- tColonisation and Landscape Transformation: Cross-Cultural Interactions in the Cimmerian Bosporus Region -- tThe Female Burial at Karagodeuashkh -- tGyenos: Reflections on Etymology in Colchis and Tales of Argonauts and Giants -- tA Few Remarks on the Naukleroi of the Cities on the Southern Shore of the Black Sea during the Imperial Period -- tCults in Ancient Sinope: Originality and Standardisation -- tContributors -- tIndex of Names (People, Places etc.) -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEnvironment and human habitation have become principal topics of research with the growing interest in the Black Sea region in antiquity. This book highlights their interaction around all the coasts of the region, from different perspectives and disciplines. Here, archaeological excavation and survey combine with studies of classical texts, cults, medicine, and more, to explore ancient experiences of the region. Accordingly, the region is examined from external viewpoints, centred in the Mediterranean (Herodotus, the Hippocratics, ancient geographers, and poets), and through local lenses, particularly supplied by archaeology. While familiar disconnects emerge, there is also a striking coherence in the results of these different pathways into the study of local environments, which embrace not only Graeco-Roman settlement, but also a broader range of agricultural and pastoralist activities across a huge landscape which stretches as far afield as ancient Hungary. Throughout, there are methodological implications for research elsewhere in the ancient world. This book shows people in landscapes across a huge expanse, in local reality and in external conceptions, complete with their own agency, ideas, and lifestyles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aAntike Kulte. 4aAusgrabungen und Survey. 4aMittelmeerregion. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAncient Mediterranean.  aBlack Sea region.  aancient history of everyday life.  acults.1 aAndresen, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvram, Alexandru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaralis, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarat, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraund, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraund, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCraik, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamyanov, Margarit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco Chiai, Gian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavrylyuk, Nadiya A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrumeza, Lavinia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLungu, Vasilica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOller Guzmán, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanayotova, Krastina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeter, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeter, Ulrike, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetropoulos, Elias K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReho, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4h